{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d2d5aefd-3139-4968-980c-93f6fa06ca42","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n**Why:** After a .NET SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may be pinned to versions that are incompatible with the new SDK. `dotnet workload update` downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all workloads that match your current SDK band.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** would **not** help here — it reinstalls the *same versions* you already have. It's meant for fixing corrupted installations, not version mismatches.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still see issues after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed and matches your target SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9021617-e7e8-4fc7-9086-bf9643ca51fe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a .NET SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not tied to any code in the working directory. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the installed SDK band. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations, but does **not** change versions. \n\n`repair` just re-downloads and reinstalls the same versions, so after an SDK update it would leave you with incompatible workloads. The right move is `dotnet workload update` to get versions that work with the new SDK.","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"1103:DD840:BEE606:DEE6EB:69FE84FA"},"id":"ebf638af-3b93-4473-b5eb-a1e42f6c4d58","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:17.201Z","parentId":"66dd4e5c-c94c-41ee-89f0-ec7df808d238"}
